title: Definition and Tarski's Axioms of Geometry

  |- wbr(c0, cstr, cop(nat1, cdc(nat1, nat6)))
  -| wceq(c0, ctp(cop(cfv(cbs, cnx), c1), cop(cfv(cds, cnx), c2), cop(cfv(citv, cnx), c3)))
} = {
  eqbrtri(c0, cstr, cop(nat1, cdc(nat1, nat6)), ctp(cop(cfv(cbs, cnx), c1), cop(cfv(cds, cnx), c2), cop(cfv(citv, cnx), c3)))
  strle3(cfv(cbs, cnx), c1, cfv(cds, cnx), c2, cfv(citv, cnx), c3, nat1, cdc(nat1, nat6), cdc(nat1, nat2))
  basendx()

  decnncl(nat1, nat2)

  declt(nat1, nat2, nat6)

thm trkgstr(class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3) {
  ⊢ c0[Struct]< 1, cdc(1, 6)>

  basendx()

blocks.name: df-trkgc
blocks.content: Define the class of geometries fulfilling the congruence axioms of reflexivity, identity and transitivity. These are axioms A1 to A3 of [Schwabhauser] p. 10. With our distance based notation for congruence, transitivity of congruence boils down to transitivity of equality and is already given by ~ eqtr , so it is not listed in this definition. (Contributed by Thierry Arnoux, 24-Aug-2017.)

blocks.name: df-trkgld
blocks.content: Define the class of geometries fulfilling the lower dimension axiom for dimension ` n ` . For such geometries, there are three non-colinear points that are equidistant from ` n - 1 ` distinct points. Derived from remarks in _Tarski's System of Geometry_, Alfred Tarski and Steven Givant, Bulletin of Symbolic Logic, Volume 5, Number 2 (1999), 175-214. (Contributed by Scott Fenton, 22-Apr-2013.) blocks.name: df-trkg
blocks.content:
Define the class of Tarski geometries. A Tarski geometry is a set of points, equipped with a betweenness relation (denoting that a point lies on a line segment between two other points) and a congruence relation (denoting equality of line segment lengths). Here, we are using the following:
  • for congruence, ` ( x .- y ) = ( z .- w ) ` where ` .- = ( dist `` W ) `
  • for betweenness, ` y e. ( x I z ) ` , where ` I = ( Itv `` W ) `
With this definition, the axiom A2 is actually equivalent to the transitivity of addition, ~ eqtrd .

Tarski originally had more axioms, but later reduced his list to 11:

  • A1 A kind of reflexivity for the congruence relation (TarskiGC)
  • A2 Transitivity for the congruence relation ( ` TarskiGC ` )
  • A3 Identity for the congruence relation ( ` TarskiGC ` )
  • A4 Axiom of segment construction ( ` TarskiGCB ` )
  • A5 5-segment axiom ( ` TarskiGCB ` )
  • A6 Identity for the betweenness relation ( ` TarskiGB ` )
  • A7 Axiom of Pasch ( ` TarskiGB ` )
  • A8 Lower dimension axiom ` ( TarskiGDim>= `` 2 ) `
  • A9 Upper dimension axiom ` ( _V \ ( TarskiGDim>= `` 3 ) ) `
  • A10 Euclid's axiom ( ` TarskiGE ` )
  • A11 Axiom of continuity ( ` TarskiGB ` )
Our definition is split into 5 parts:
  • congruence axioms ` TarskiGC ` (which metric spaces fulfill)
  • betweenness axioms ` TarskiGB `
  • congruence and betweenness axioms ` TarskiGCB `
  • upper and lower dimension axioms ` TarskiGDim>= `
  • axiom of Euclid / parallel postulate ` TarskiGE `
So our definition of a Tarskian Geometry includes the 3 axioms for the quaternary congruence relation (A1, A2, A3), the 3 axioms for the ternary betweenness relation (A6, A7, A11), and the 2 axioms of compatibility of the congruence and the betweenness relations (A4,A5). It does not include Euclid's axiom A10, nor the 2-dimensional axioms A8 (Lower dimension axiom) and A9 (Upper dimension axiom) so the number of dimensions of the geometry it formalizes is not constrained. Considering A2 as one of the 3 axioms for the quaternary congruence relation is somewhat conventional, because the transitivity of the congruence relation is automatically given by our choice to take the distance as this congruence relation in our definition of Tarski geometries. (Contributed by Thierry Arnoux, 24-Aug-2017.) (Revised by Thierry Arnoux, 27-Apr-2019.)

blocks.name: axtgsegcon
blocks.content: Axiom of segment construction, Axiom A4 of [Schwabhauser] p. 11. As discussed in Axiom 4 of [Tarski1999] p. 178, "The intuitive content [is that] given any line segment ` A B ` , one can construct a line segment congruent to it, starting at any point ` Y ` and going in the direction of any ray containing ` Y ` . The ray is determined by the point ` Y ` and a second point ` X ` , the endpoint of the ray. The other endpoint of the line segment to be constructed is just the point ` z ` whose existence is asserted." (Contributed by Thierry Arnoux, 15-Mar-2019.)

blocks.name: axtg5seg
blocks.content: Five segments axiom, Axiom A5 of [Schwabhauser] p. 11. Take two triangles ` X Z U ` and ` A C V ` , a point ` Y ` on ` X Z ` , and a point ` B ` on ` A C ` . If all corresponding line segments except for ` Z U ` and ` C V ` are congruent ( i.e., ` X Y .~ A B ` , ` Y Z .~ B C ` , ` X U .~ A V ` , and ` Y U .~ B V ` ), then ` Z U ` and ` C V ` are also congruent. As noted in Axiom 5 of [Tarski1999] p. 178, "this axiom is similar in character to the well-known theorems of Euclidean geometry that allow one to conclude, from hypotheses about the congruence of certain corresponding sides and angles in two triangles, the congruence of other corresponding sides and angles." (Contributed by Thierry Arnoux, 14-Mar-2019.)

blocks.name: axtgpasch
blocks.content: Axiom of (Inner) Pasch, Axiom A7 of [Schwabhauser] p. 12. Given triangle ` X Y Z ` , point ` U ` in segment ` X Z ` , and point ` V ` in segment ` Y Z ` , there exists a point ` a ` on both the segment ` U Y ` and the segment ` V X ` . This axiom is essentially a subset of the general Pasch axiom. The general Pasch axiom asserts that on a plane "a line intersecting a triangle in one of its sides, and not intersecting any of the vertices, must intersect one of the other two sides" (per the discussion about Axiom 7 of [Tarski1999] p. 179). The (general) Pasch axiom was used implicitly by Euclid, but never stated; Moritz Pasch discovered its omission in 1882. As noted in the Metamath book, this means that the omission of Pasch's axiom from Euclid went unnoticed for 2000 years. Only the inner Pasch algorithm is included as an axiom; the "outer" form of the Pasch axiom can be proved using the inner form (see theorem 9.6 of [Schwabhauser] p. 69 and the brief discussion in axiom 7.1 of [Tarski1999] p. 180). (Contributed by Thierry Arnoux, 15-Mar-2019.)

blocks.name: axtgcont1
blocks.content: Axiom of Continuity. Axiom A11 of [Schwabhauser] p. 13. This axiom (scheme) asserts that any two sets ` S ` and ` T ` (of points) such that the elements of ` S ` precede the elements of ` T ` with respect to some point ` a ` (that is, ` x ` is between ` a ` and ` y ` whenever ` x ` is in ` X ` and ` y ` is in ` Y ` ) are separated by some point ` b ` ; this is explained in Axiom 11 of [Tarski1999] p. 185. (Contributed by Thierry Arnoux, 16-Mar-2019.)

  ⊢ (w0 → ∃(s0 ∈ c0, ∀(s1 ∈ c1, ∀(s2 ∈ c2, s0 ∈(s1[c3]s2)))))

  ⊣ (w0 → c2 ⊆ c0)
  ⊣ (w0 → c6 ∈ c0)
  ⊣ ((w0 ∧ s3 ∈ c1 ∧ s4 ∈ c2)→ s3 ∈(c6[c3]s4))

} = {
  a1ii((w0 → ∃(s0 ∈ c0, ∀(s1 ∈ c1, ∀(s2 ∈ c2, s0 ∈(s1[c3]s2))))), d(s0, s3))
  a1ii((w0 → ∃(s0 ∈ c0, ∀(s1 ∈ c1, ∀(s2 ∈ c2, s0 ∈(s1[c3]s2))))), d(s0, s4))
  a1ii((w0 → ∃(s0 ∈ c0, ∀(s1 ∈ c1, ∀(s2 ∈ c2, s0 ∈(s1[c3]s2))))), d(s0, c6))
  a1ii((w0 → ∃(s0 ∈ c0, ∀(s1 ∈ c1, ∀(s2 ∈ c2, s0 ∈(s1[c3]s2))))), d(s3, c0))

  syl2anc(w0, ∃(hs0 ∈ c0, ∀(s1 ∈ c1, ∀(s2 ∈ c2, s1 ∈(hs0[c3]s2)))), c6 ∈ c0, ∀(s3 ∈ c1, ∀(s4 ∈ c2, s3 ∈(c6[c3]s4))))
  ralrimivva(s3, s4, c1, c2, w0, s3 ∈(c6[c3]s4))
  3expb(w0, s3 ∈ c1, s4 ∈ c2, s3 ∈(c6[c3]s4))
  rspcev(hs0, c6, c0, ∀(s3 ∈ c1, ∀(s4 ∈ c2, s3 ∈(c6[c3]s4))), ∀(s1 ∈ c1, ∀(s2 ∈ c2, s1 ∈(hs0[c3]s2))))

  eleq12d(s1, (hs0[c3]s2), s3, (c6[c3]s4), ((hs0 = c6 ∧ s1 = s3)∧ s2 = s4))
  simplr(hs0 = c6, s1 = s3, s2 = s4)
  oveq12d(hs0, c3, s2, c6, s4, ((hs0 = c6 ∧ s1 = s3)∧ s2 = s4))
  simpll(hs0 = c6, s1 = s3, s2 = s4)
  simpr((hs0 = c6 ∧ s1 = s3), s2 = s4)
  axtgcont1(hs0, s1, s2, s0, c0, c1, c2, c3, c4, c5, w0)

  diff.cv.s(s1, s4)
  diff.wceq.s(s3, hs0, c6)
  diff.wral.s(s3, s2, c2, s1 ∈(hs0[c3]s2))
  diff.wcel.s(s3, s1, (hs0[c3]s2))
  diff.cv.s(s3, s1)

  diff.cv.s(s2, s4)
  diff.wa.s(s4, hs0 = c6, s1 = s3)
  diff.wceq.s(s4, hs0, c6)
  diff.wceq.s(s4, s1, s3)
  diff.cv.s(s4, s3)
  diffss.ex(s4, s3)
  diff.wcel.s(s4, s1, (hs0[c3]s2))
  diff.cv.s(s4, s1)

  diffss.ex(s1, s0)
  diffss.ex(s2, s0)
  diff.hs0.c(c1)
  diff.hs0.c(c2)
  diff.hs0.c(c3)
  diff.hs0.c(c5)
}

blocks.content: Lower dimension axiom for dimension 2, Axiom A8 of [Schwabhauser] p. 13. There exist 3 non-colinear points. (Contributed by Thierry Arnoux, 20-Nov-2019.)

thm axtglowdim2(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, class c4, wff w0) {
  |- wi(w0, wrex(s0, c0, wrex(s1, c0, wrex(s2, c0, wn(w3o(wcel(cv(s2), co(cv(s0), c1, cv(s1))), wcel(cv(s0), co(cv(s2), c1, cv(s1))), wcel(cv(s1), co(cv(s0), c1, cv(s2)))))))))
  -| wceq(c0, cfv(cbs, c2))
  -| wceq(c3, cfv(cds, c2))
  -| wceq(c1, cfv(citv, c2))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c2, c4))
  -| wi(w0, wbr(c2, cstrkgld, nat2))
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffss(s0, s2)
  -| diffss(s1, s2)
  -| diffsc(s0, c0)
  -| diffsc(s0, c1)
  -| diffsc(s0, c3)
  -| diffsc(s1, c0)
  -| diffsc(s1, c1)
  -| diffsc(s1, c3)
  -| diffsc(s2, c0)
  -| diffsc(s2, c1)
  -| diffsc(s2, c3)
} = {
  mpbid(w0, wrex(s0, c0, wrex(s1, c0, wrex(s2, c0, wn(w3o(wcel(cv(s2), co(cv(s0), c1, cv(s1))), wcel(cv(s0), co(cv(s2), c1, cv(s1))), wcel(cv(s1), co(cv(s0), c1, cv(s2)))))))), wbr(c2, cstrkgld, nat2))
  syl(w0, wb(wbr(c2, cstrkgld, nat2), wrex(s0, c0, wrex(s1, c0, wrex(s2, c0, wn(w3o(wcel(cv(s2), co(cv(s0), c1, cv(s1))), wcel(cv(s0), co(cv(s2), c1, cv(s1))), wcel(cv(s1), co(cv(s0), c1, cv(s2))))))))), wcel(c2, c4))
  istrkg2ld(s0, s1, s2, c2, c4, c0, c1, c3)
}

  ⊣ d(s0, s1)

  mpbid(w0, ∃(s0 ∈ c0, ∃(s1 ∈ c0, ∃(s2 ∈ c0, ¬(s2 ∈(s0[c1]s1)∨ s0 ∈(s2[c1]s1)∨ s1 ∈(s0[c1]s2))))), c2[TarskiGDim> =]2)
  syl(w0, (c2[TarskiGDim> =]2 ↔ ∃(s0 ∈ c0, ∃(s1 ∈ c0, ∃(s2 ∈ c0, ¬(s2 ∈(s0[c1]s1)∨ s0 ∈(s2[c1]s1)∨ s1 ∈(s0[c1]s2)))))), c2 ∈ c4)

blocks.name: axtgupdim2
blocks.content: Upper dimension axiom for dimension 2, Axiom A9 of [Schwabhauser] p. 13. Three points ` X ` , ` Y ` and ` Z ` equidistant to two given two points ` U ` and ` V ` must be colinear. (Contributed by Thierry Arnoux, 29-May-2019.) (Revised by Thierry Arnoux, 11-Jul-2020.)

thm axtgupdim2(class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, class c4, class c5, class c6, class c7, class c8, wff w0) {
  |- wi(w0, w3o(wcel(c0, co(c1, c2, c3)), wcel(c1, co(c0, c2, c3)), wcel(c3, co(c1, c2, c0))))
